{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622435"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:02:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:02:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16797"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16797"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.56,0,0.16,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76686"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9488"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16797"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62178"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5148"},{"type":"tags","id":"7104"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"},{"type":"tags","id":"10313"},{"type":"tags","id":"10315"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22786"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76686"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAnticholinergic medications are commonly used to treat various conditions including overactive bladder, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, and motion sickness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of anticholinergic drugs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Competitively block primarily nicotinic receptors","Competitively block primarily muscarinic receptors","Degrade acetylcholine in the synaptic cleft","Competitively block acetylcholine synthesis","Competitively block acetylcholine release from nerve terminals"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAnticholinergic drugs act within central and peripheral nervous system synapses, competitively inhibiting parasympathetic activity. Their mechanism of action is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompetitively block primarily muscarinic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E, preventing acetylcholine from binding and activating these receptors. This results in reduced parasympathetic activity in various organ systems, a mechanism that can be used for a variety of therapeutic purposes. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetitively block primarily nicotinic receptors \u003C/strong\u003E- anticholinergics predominantly act at muscarinic receptors \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetitively block acetylcholine synthesis \u003C/strong\u003E- Anticholinergic drugs do not interfere with the production of acetylcholine in nerve terminals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDegrade acetylcholine in the synaptic cleft\u003C/strong\u003E- This describes the action of acetylcholinesterase enzyme, which is different from anticholinergic drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetitively block acetylcholine release from nerve terminals\u003C/strong\u003E- This is the mechanism of action for botulinum toxin rather than anticholinergic medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon anticholinergic effects include dry mouth (reduced salivation), urinary retention (reduced bladder contraction), constipation (reduced gut motility), blurred vision (pupillary dilation), and tachycardia (reduced vagal tone).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anticholinergic drugs competitively block acetylcholine at muscarinic receptors.","Anticholinergic side effects include dry mouth, urinary retention, constipation, blurred vision, and tachycardia.","Atropine is a commonly used anticholinergic drug derived from Atropa belladonna."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62178"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16797"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62178"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T09:25:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T09:25:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9488"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76686"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":